@node "WhatsScreenFool" "What is ScreenFool?"
What Is ScreenFool?

ScreenFool is a utility for Amigas with Release 2 or later of the operating
system.  It allows you to work with so-called "Public" screens and thereby
enhance your productivity, by allowing Workbench screen (and other)
applications to use a different screen than the regular Workbench.
@endnode

@node "FeatureList" "ScreenFool's features"
Features:

ScreenFool has three main interfaces: the Intuition (GUI) interface, the
Commodities (hot-key) interface, and the ARexx macro interface.

Some features of the Intuition interface include:

ˇ Open a public screen in any available Intuition-supported display mode. *

ˇ Close any open public screen.

ˇ Make all windows that open on Workbench open on another screen (@{"SHANGHAI" link "Glossary" 0}).

ˇ Set a @{"default public screen" link "Glossary" 0} for applications.

ˇ Pop a screen to front when a visitor window appears on it (@{"AUTOPOP" link "Glossary" 0}).

ˇ Change public screen palettes.

ˇ @{"Localization" link "Localization" 0} under Release 2.1 and above.

ˇ @{"Font-sensitive" link "FontSensitivity" 0} GUI.

The Commodities interface supports:

ˇ Commodities Exchange control of the program window.

ˇ Hiding and showing the control window.

ˇ Hotkey access.

The ARexx interface supports:

ˇ All Intuition and Commodities interface functions, plus:

ˇ Obtaining information on available screens and display modes

ˇ Numeric palette setting

ˇ Options not included in the GUI.

Workbench.library support:

ˇ Pop up the window at any time from Workbench's Tools menu.

* Full capability requires a keyfile that will be sent upon @{"registration" link "LegalStuff" 0}
@endnode

@node "RequiredStuff" "System Requirements"
System Requirements:

 * AmigaDOS Release 2 or later (Intuition V37)
 * 512K RAM (Much more recommended if you're opening many screens)
 * Any processor

ScreenFool is compatible with advanced processors and Release 3. It has been
tested on a V37 (final) A2000 system with 3 MB RAM, 80 MB hard disk, and 68000
processor (7.14 MHz); and on a V39 A4000 system with 8 MB RAM, 120 MB hard
disk, and 68040 processor (25 MHz).
@endnode

