@node "FontSensitivity" "The Font-Sensitive GUI"
The Font-Sensitive GUI:

ScreenFool Release 2.4U added the additional feature of a font-sensitive GUI
to the ScreenFool interface. Basically, ScreenFool tries to adapt to the
screen font of screens that it opens on.

There are certain limitations to this feature:

  1) If the screen font is greater than 18 point, the GUI reverts to topaz.
  
  2) If ScreenFool thinks that the screen is too small to display the full
     window, ScreenFool will revert to topaz 8, or the BACKUPFONT set in the
     @{"Tool Types" link "Options" 0}. If topaz or BACKUPFONT is still too large, ScreenFool
     will attempt to use SystemThin.font 8 point, which is a narrow font
     supplied with ProWrite, or the SMALLFONT set in the @{"Tool Types" link "Options" 0}.
     ** SystemThin.font IS NOT REQUIRED FOR SCREENFOOL TO WORK.
  
  3) If your font has a tf_XSize somewhere in the vicinity of machine
     infinity, as is the case with many poorly designed fonts, ScreenFool
     will go through the steps as outlined in limitation 2, above.

  4) The window may look odd at point sizes outside the 6-12 range. This is
     due to the fact that ScreenFool has not been extensively tested with
     very large and very small fonts.
  
  5) Under Release 3 and later, the checkmarks are scaled if the font is
     greater than 11 points tall.

Please let me know about any enhancements you would like to see in the GUI
font adaptivity.
@endnode

@node "Localization" "ScreenFool and Localization"
Localization:

ScreenFool 3.0 and above include language localization features. As demand for
different languages becomes apparent, I will release new language catalogs for
ScreenFool.

The current release includes the following languages:

 ˇ English (internal)
 ˇ Franįais

Please note that Release 2.1 or later of the Amiga operating system is
required for localization to work.

If you would like to localize ScreenFool to your language, follow the
following steps:

 1. Edit the @{b}ScreenFool_translation.ct@{ub} file, translating the provided English
    strings to your language.
 2. Send the completed file to me, either by electronic or snail mail.

I will create the catalog file and mail it to you. In addition, your
translation may be included with the next public release of ScreenFool. If
this is the case, you will receive either a free registration or a refund of
your registration fee.

Inclusion of translations is at the sole discretion of the author (me).
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
Installation:

ScreenFool 3.0 and above include an Installer script. To install ScreenFool,
you'll need a copy of Installer somewhere in your search path (check your
operating system Install disk if you don't already have Installer on your hard
drive).

Double-click on the Installer icon to begin the installation process. If you
choose a "User Level" of Novice, the program will automatically be installed
to your SYS:WBStartup directory; otherwise, you will be able to choose from
three installation options: SYS:WBStartup, SYS:Tools/Commodities, or
Custom...

Installing to one of the Boot volume directories will install the libraries,
this help file, and catalog files to the default system directories.  This
method is recommended if you will use ScreenFool often.

You can also install to a Custom directory. This will create a drawer called
ScreenFool which contains all of the files ScreenFool needs to operate;
however, reqtools.library will still be installed to your Libs: path (if
necessary).
@endnode

@node "Glossary" "Some basic terminology"
Terms You Need To Know:

PUBLIC SCREEN: A screen that other programs are allowed to open windows on.
  Intuition V36 (Release 2.0) and later support this feature. Many programs
  can open on a public screen.

DEFAULT SCREEN: The screen that applications that do not open their own
  screen will open onto. For pre-V36 applications, this was Workbench.
  Newer applications will go to this screen.

VISITOR WINDOW: A window on a public screen opened by an application that
  didn't open the screen. The ScreenFool main window is a visitor window,
  as is the IconEdit window.

DISPLAY ID: A number that represents a specific display mode. For example,
  a low resolution, non-interlaced screen has a display ID of 0. For more
  details, see the @{"Display ID reference" link "DisplayIDs" 0}.

MODE PROMOTION: A feature of Release 3 (V39) of graphics.library, which
  allows some screen modes to be essentially replaced by others. For
  example, DBLNTSC:High Res No Flicker replaces NTSC:High Res Laced.
  ScreenFool fully supports Mode Promotion.

FLAG: A variable that can only have a value of on or off.

SHANGHAI: A system flag that determines the behavior of the default public
  screen. If this flag is set, pre-V36 applications will open on the
  default public screen, even if they ask for Workbench.

AUTOPOP: A system flag that makes a public screen to pop to the front when a
  visitor window opens on it.

INTERLEAVED BITMAP: A screen type, only available in Release 3 and later,
  which improves the display on many-bitplane screens by reducing the
  "color flashing" during scrolling. ScreenFool opens its screens on
  V39 systems as interleaved, unless you override this behavior.
  Pre-V39 systems use a "standard bitmap," as does V39 if you use the
  @{"NEW NOTINTERLEAVED" link "New" 0} macro command.
@endnode

@node "HowToUse" "Running and Using ScreenFool"
Running And Using:

To run ScreenFool from the Workbench, double-click the Commodity icon labelled
@{b}ScreenFool@{ub} (if you are using a 68020 or higher computer, use the icon labelled
@{b}ScreenFool-AP@{ub}).

To run ScreenFool from the Shell, type "ScreenFool" at the command prompt. If
you want to continue using the current shell window, type:

@{b}run <nil: >nil: ScreenFool@{ub}

If you wish to set startup options from either Workbench or the Shell, see the
section on @{"Tool Types" link "Options" 0}.

The @{"ScreenFool window" link "SFWindow.IFF/main" 0} will then be displayed. This window allows you to
manipulate the screens in the scrolling list.

The action gadgets on the right of the scrolling list (from top) will open a
new screen, close the selected screen, and change the selected  screen to the
default screen.

The two checkboxes, @{"Shanghai" link "Shanghai_GUI" 0} and @{"AutoPop" link "AutoPop_GUI" 0} change the behavior of all Public
screens. Both default to OFF on the Amiga under Releases 2 and 3.

The two message lines at the bottom of the window display the name of the
default screen and messages from executed commands. The status line might say
'Couldn't close screen' if you tried to close a screen with windows still open
on it, for example.

Other features are concealed in the menus. All choices have keyboard
equivalents. Note that you may use either Right Amiga-key combinations or the
letter on its own. By menu, they are:

Project Menu:

  @{"About..." link "About_GUI" 0} (?) - Display program information.
  @{"Hide" link "Hide_GUI" 0} (H) - Conceal program user interface.
  @{"Quit" link "Quit_GUI" 0} (Q) - Exit the program.

Screen Menu:

  @{"New..." link "New_GUI" 0} (N) - Open a new screen.
  @{"Close" link "Close_GUI" 0} (C) - Close selected screen.
  @{"Make Default" link "Default_GUI" 0} (D) - Make the selected screen the default screen.
  @{"To Front" link "Front_GUI" 0} (F) - Bring selected screen to front of stack.
  @{"To Back" link "Back_GUI" 0} (B) - Move selected screen to back of stack.
  @{"Palette..." link "Palette_GUI" 0} (P) - Change the palette for selected screen.
  @{"Write Palette..." link "WritePalette_GUI" 0} (W) - Write a screen's palette to a script.
  @{"Information..." link "Info_GUI" 0} (I) - Show screen name, resolution, etc.

Tools Menu:

  @{"Jump Window" link "Jump_GUI" 0} (J) - Jump the ScreenFool window to the selected screen.
  @{"Update Display" link "Update_GUI" 0} (U) - Refresh scrolling and display mode lists.
  @{"Help..." link "UserHelp_GUI" 0} (L) - Get information on various topics.

Macro Menu:

  @{"Command..." link "Command_GUI" 0} (X) - Execute a single command line.
  @{"Macro ģ Console..." link "MacCon_GUI" 0} (,) - Execute an ARexx macro with a window to
    display the output.
  @{"Macro ģ No Console..." link "Macro_GUI" 0} (M) - Execute an ARexx macro without a window
    to display any output (output redirected to NIL:).

For further information on menu choices, pull down the menu to the option you
want information for, and then press Help BEFORE releasing the right mouse
button.

Important note: Help is only available if the file ScreenFool.guide is in the
directory that ScreenFool is launched from, the LOCALE:Help/English directory,
or in a directory in the AmigaGuide search path.
@endnode

@node "Options" "Tool Types"
Tool Types and Shell Options:

These options can be added to the Tool Types by using the "Icons ģ
Information..." option on the Workbench. From the Shell, they can be used by
following the ScreenFool command with the tool type and its option, in quotes,
as below:

ScreenFool "TYPE1=OPTION1" "TYPE2=OPTION2" ...

The available Tool Types are:

DONOTWAIT - Make sure this Tool Type is included if ScreenFool will be run
  in WBStartup.

CX_POPUP - YES to have window pop up immediately when run; NO to hide window
  until summoned by hotkey or Commodities Exchange. Default: YES.

CX_POPKEY - The key specification for the keypress that will pop up the
  window. Default is "Control F1". The keypress combinations are listed on
  page 5-29 of "Using the System Software" (2.0 users) and on page 10-25 of
  the "Workbench 3.0" manual.

CX_PRIORITY - Sets relative priority of the ScreenFool program, from 127
  to -128 (to other commodities). Defaults to 0.

STARTUP - ARexx macro to automatically run on startup. Defaults to 
  "SF-Startup". ScreenFool uses a ".sf" extension on its macros, so
  SF-Startup.sf would be the proper name for the startup macro.

PORTNAME - Name for the ARexx port. Normally "ScreenFool.1".

PUBSCREEN - Name of the screen for ScreenFool to initially open on. Will
  normally open on the default screen.

COMMAND - A single macro command to run when the program initially starts.
  Normally there is no command.

REXXDIR - Default macro directory. REXX: if omitted.

BACKUPFONT - Font to use when screen font is too large. The default is
  topaz.font.

BACKUPSIZE - Point size for BACKUPFONT; defaults to 8.

SMALLFONT - Font to use when screen and backup fonts are too large. The
  default is SystemThin.font.

SMALLSIZE - Point size for SMALLFONT; defaults to 8.

WEIRDMODES - Set WEIRDMODES=YES if you want to see Extra Halfbrite and HAM
  modes in the New Screen requester. Defaults to NO.

FINDKEY - Set to NO if you want to disable the Keyfile search. Defaults
  to YES.
@endnode

@node "About_GUI" "About: Obtain program information (GUI)"
@{fg highlight}Project ģ About...@{fg text}

This option gives the version of the program, its registration status, the
name of the ARexx port, and a summary of available Chip and Fast RAM.

Hotkey: @{fg highlight}Amiga-?@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "Hide_GUI" "Hide: Hide the control window (GUI)"
@{fg highlight}Project ģ Hide@{fg text}

Hide the main window. The window can be brought back up again by pressing the
Commodities hotkey for this program (default: Control F1), by choosing "Show"
in the Commodities Exchange program, or by using the Workbench Tools menu.

Hotkey: @{fg highlight}Amiga-H@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "Quit_GUI" "Quit: Exit ScreenFool (GUI)"
@{fg highlight}Project ģ Quit@{fg text}

Quit ScreenFool. This can also be accomplished by using the Commodities "Kill"
button, or by breaking the ScreenFool process (using Control-C or the Shell
BREAK command).

Hotkey: @{fg highlight}Amiga-Q@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "New_GUI" "New: Open a new screen (GUI)"
 @{fg highlight}Screen ģ New...@{fg text}
 @{fg highlight}New Screen...@{fg text} (Action button)

Opens a new screen, duplicating the characteristics of the screen that the
main window is currently open on.

Under Release 3 or later, the screen will be @{"interleaved" link "Glossary" 32}.

If you register, you will be able to manipulate the options for the new screen
in a @{"requester" link "SFNewScrReq.IFF/main" 0}.

The Listview gadget contains the available display modes.

The Screen Name text gadget is used to enter a name for the public screen.
This name must be unique.

The Overscan cycle gadget allows you to choose from Text, Graphics (Standard),
Maximum and Video overscan settings.

The Bitplanes slider gadget allows you to choose the number of bitplanes the
screen should use (use the left and right cursor keys to change it from the
keyboard). Note that all depths may not be available with HAM and EHB
displays, so use care.

The Width and Height integer gadgets and check-boxes allow you to choose the
screen's width and height. Note that you can't change the width and height of
OSCAN_VIDEO screens.

The Like Workbench checkbox, under Release 3 and later, allows you to create a
screen that is a direct clone of the Workbench screen automatically.

The Interleaved Screen checkbox, under Release 3 and later, creates a screen
that has properties that reduce flickering during scrolling.

Note that help is not available directly from the @{fg highlight}Open New Screen...@{fg text}
requester. This will be rectified in a later release.

Hotkey: @{fg highlight}Amiga-N@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "Close_GUI" "Close: Close a public screen (GUI)"
 @{fg highlight}Screen ģ Close@{fg text}
 @{fg highlight}Close Screen@{fg text} (Action button)

Close the currently selected public screen. The screen will not close if any
windows are currently open on it.

The screen need not have been opened by ScreenFool.

Hotkey: @{fg highlight}Amiga-C@{fg text}
@endnode

@node "Default_GUI" "Make Default: Change the default public screen (GUI)"
 @{fg highlight}Screen ģ Make Default@{fg text}
