not be reproduced without their express written consent.

Damned is he who wears the yellow hat. -- I Corinthians 22:6
@endnode

@node "DisplayIDs" "Appendix: Display ID reference"
@prev "EndNotes"
This is a brief guide to the most often-used available DisplayIDs in
ScreenFool.  A more complete list can be found using @{"GetAttr Displays" link "GetAttr" 0} (as
demonstrated in the script SFTest.sf). Note that display IDs returned by this
function are absolute (monitor-specific), not generic.

Use the generic IDs in scripts for compatibility with Mode Promotion and
international systems. Unrecognized display IDs are converted to generic HiRes
in attempt to recover from script errors.

Please note that several monitors are not included in this list, notably the
Euro36 and Euro72 monitors (which provide European systems with NTSC
resolutions at higher refresh rates) and the Super72 monitor.

Default.monitor (NTSC/PAL/DblNTSC/DblPAL)

 Name                Resolution             Display ID           Display ID
                                             (hex)               (decimal)

 LowRes              320x200 (256)š˛            0x0                   0

 HiRes               640x200 (256)˛          0x8000               32768

 SuperHiRes         1280x200 (256)           0x8020               32800

 LowResLace          320x400 (512)˛             0x4                   4

 HiResLace           640x400 (512)˛          0x8004               32772

 SuperHiResLace     1280x400 (512)           0x8024               32804


Multisync.monitor (VGA/Multisync) *

 Productivity        640x480 ŗ              0x39024              233508
 
 ProductLaced        640x960 ŗ              0x39025              233509


Doublescan (AGA) monitors *

 LoRes-DblLace        320x800 (1024)           0x5                    5
 
 HiRes-DblLace        640x800 (1024)        0x8005                32773


š Parentheses indicate PAL (50 Hz) vertical resolution. These resolutions are
non-overscan and typical of Pre-2.0 screens.

˛ Promoted by Mode Promotion

ŗ No overscan

* These resolutions require a VGA or Multisync monitor
@endnode

@node "VersNotes" "Appendix: A Note About Version Numbers"
There are two "revision tracks" for ScreenFool. They are Regular and Advanced
Processor. The version string of the program depends on what track of
ScreenFool you are using.

The regular version has version strings of the format:

ScreenFool x.x (d.m.y)

The advanced processor version has a version string like:

ScreenFool x.x-AP020 (d.m.y)
@endnode

@node "RevisionHistory" "Appendix: Revision History"
The following is a brief revision history of ScreenFool.

This Version: ScreenFool 3.0a (**INTERIM**)

@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 2.7 (5.9.94)@{uu}

* Localization! Maintenant, on peut utiliser ScreenFool en franįais!
  (A .ct file is included, for your edification.)

* Uses @{b}Installer@{ub}. Now, two installation choices: If you run ScreenFool out
  of one directory, you can install the entire system there. Or, if you run
  it in WBStartup or Commodities, install the files to system directories.

* Shortcut for @{"Screen ģ Palette..." link "Palette_GUI" 0} changed to Amiga-P from Amiga-E.
  (Forgot that P had been unused since I got my Amiga User Interface Style
   Guide & changed AutoPop to A (from P) and About to ? (from A))

* Fixed bug that made ScreenFool crash if you did a GETATTR DISPLAYS and
  there were more than about 40 modes available. Upper limit increased to
  around 120.
  Thanks to Nigel Davidson for reporting this.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 2.6 (17.8.94)@{uu}

* Direct setting of RGB values now available in the @{"PALETTE" link "Palette" 0} macro command.

* New @{"GETPALETTE" link "GetPalette" 0} macro command to get specified palette entries.

* Includes ablity to @{"write a screen's palette" link "WritePalette_GUI" 0} to a script file.

* Includes Advanced Processor version in standard distribution.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 2.5U (13.1.94)@{uu}

* Registered and Unregistered releases combined into one program. Currently
  registered users will receive a keyfile that enables the New Screen
  requester.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 2.4U (11.9.93)@{uu}

* @{"UPDATE" link "Update_GUI" 0} function now expanded in scope. May now force a mode list update.

* Window disable functions implemented using more speed-efficient methods.

* Main program and library recompiled using SAS/C 6.51 -- better optimizer,
  smaller code size.

* Library memory fragmentation greatly reduced.

* Replaced extended character × with x, for better compatibility with
  non-Amiga fonts.

* Registered version requester now has better unusual screenmode 
  identification and supports RTG monitors better (you set planes rather
  than colors).

* Fixed bug with screen information requester not properly identifying
  display modes without names.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 2.3U (6.9.93)@{uu}

* Help file improved; incorrect references removed.

* Registered version mode requester improved.

* Now has a @{"font-sensitive" link "FontSensitivity" 0} GUI.

* Bug in library that would sometimes create an empty screen list
  removed.

* New @{"tool types" link "Options" 0} are available to control fonts.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 2.2U (29.8.93)@{uu}

* Help now moved to AmigaGuide file, resulting in a code decrease of
  approximately 10K. Online help is only available if the .guide file
  is in the directory ScreenFool is started from, or in a directory
  which is listed in ENV:AmigaGuide/Path.
  
  NOTE: amigaguide.library need not be present for ScreenFool to run.
  However, no help will be available if the library is not opened.

* All documentation now in AmigaGuide format.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 2.1U (13.7.93)@{uu}

* Includes support for V39 NewLookMenus, and interleaved bitmap screens.

* Now includes better support for ReqTools V38.

* Checked with Enforcer.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 1.12U (11.7.93)@{uu}

* Screen and display management functions moved to AmigaDOS shared library.
  This transfer will benefit Amiga developers by making high-level
  management functions available for all Amiga users (Release 2+).

* Tooltype REXXDIR allows user to change default ARexx directory.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 1.11U/1.10U@{uu} (Internal revisions)

* Memory loss fixes. All commands previously caused a loss of 520 bytes
  from the system.

* Bug-fix in registered version's New Screen interface -- the colors slider
  now works correctly.

* Main window now WA_SimpleRefresh again
  (Pick a WA_#?Refresh attribute, any WA_#?Refresh attribute)

* Newer Commodities 3.0-style interface

* Fixed bug that unlocked window if hidden and reopened using AppMenu


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 1.9U (8.2.93)@{uu} 

* Recompiled with SAS/C Release 6.0 -- program slightly more efficient

* Tested on 68040-based system without problems

* Internal cleanups too numerous to mention here


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 1.8U (16.1.93)@{uu}

* Changed main window to WA_SmartRefresh

* Added available memory to About... requester

* Minor visual enhancements to About... requester

* Properly attached Activate and Deactivate ARexx commands to their actual
  synonyms, @{"UnlockGUI" link "UnlockGUI" 0} and @{"LockGUI" link "LockGUI" 0} (Previously were attached to Hide and
  Show)

* Added FONT and SIZE options to @{"NEW" link "New" 0} command. See documentation for
  further details.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 1.7U (5.1.93)@{uu} 

* Fixed bug that ate memory when an OpenPublicScreenA() failed.

* Better error reporting of why screens don't open.

* Makes window use SystemThin.font (included with ProWrite) if opened on
  a low resolution screen. If not available, uses topaz.font.
  NOTE: SystemThin.font IS NOT REQUIRED TO USE SCREENFOOL.

* Fixed bug with vertical spacing in gadgets in fonts other than 8 points
  wide (that's right, WIDE).


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 1.6U (23.12.92)@{uu}

* Fixed bug that would make status information act weird on a screen with
  a font other than 8 points tall -- that was a weird one to fix.

* Internal support for opening screens with different fonts (implemented
  via GUI for registered users) -- a command line option may be added later.
   * (Not really a change): Tested with low memory (EatMem) -- passes with
  flying colors (after your initial 40-50K load). Also tested using 
  Mungwall, MemWatch, Drip, and EatCycles.


@{u}CHANGES FROM SCREENFOOL 1.5U (19.12.92)@{uu}

* ScreenFool now kills off less of your stack space -- 8K of stack is
  sufficient.

* New ARexx command - @{"REQUESTERS [ON | OFF | TOGGLE]" link "Requesters" 0} - choose to disable
  the ScreenFool requesters for asynchronous operation without a user
  present -- helpful if your ARexx macro might stop because of a missing
  NOGUI option.

* @{"GETATTR MODES" link "GetAttr" 0} now includes the current Requesters mode.
@endnode

